WEBVTT

00:00:01.080 --> 00:00:03.800
Your app is live, so let's make sure

00:00:03.800 --> 00:00:06.760
you never lose it! In this tutorial, we

00:00:06.760 --> 00:00:09.720
push the whole repository to external storage

00:00:10.200 --> 00:00:11.560
and pull it back on demand.

00:00:12.538 --> 00:00:15.338
Backup and restore comes down to three steps

00:00:15.658 --> 00:00:18.378
. Configure a storage provider, push a backup

00:00:18.858 --> 00:00:20.378
, and restore it when you need to.

00:00:23.849 --> 00:00:26.489
Step one. We will import an existing

00:00:26.489 --> 00:00:29.289
rclone configuration. rclone supports

00:00:29.369 --> 00:00:32.729
S3, Backblaze, Google Drive, Dropbox

00:00:32.889 --> 00:00:35.769
, and many more. If you already use it, the

00:00:35.769 --> 00:00:37.849
same config imports directly.

00:00:38.955 --> 00:00:41.595
Storage imported. Your CLI can now push

00:00:41.595 --> 00:00:42.395
backups to it.

00:00:45.894 --> 00:00:48.694
Let us list the storages the CLI now knows

00:00:48.694 --> 00:00:51.334
about. Each one is a destination we can push

00:00:51.334 --> 00:00:51.974
backups to.

00:00:53.913 --> 00:00:56.873
There it is. Ready to receive backups.

00:00:59.718 --> 00:01:02.518
Step two. Push a full backup. The

00:01:02.518 --> 00:01:05.638
entire repository, app, database, files

00:01:05.718 --> 00:01:08.998
, configuration, is uploaded. Because the repository

00:01:08.998 --> 00:01:11.958
is encrypted at rest, the backup is encrypted

00:01:11.958 --> 00:01:14.278
too. No extra key management.

00:01:16.727 --> 00:01:19.367
Backup uploaded. Everything in this repo is now

00:01:19.367 --> 00:01:21.527
on the remote storage, encrypted.

00:01:25.026 --> 00:01:27.666
And the backups available on this storage. From

00:01:27.666 --> 00:01:30.306
here, restore on a brand new server is

00:01:30.306 --> 00:01:32.866
one command: the repo pull command.

00:01:36.072 --> 00:01:38.632
All your snapshots in one place. Pull

00:01:38.632 --> 00:01:40.472
any of them back with a single command.

00:01:41.490 --> 00:01:44.210
Your data is safe and portable across

00:01:44.210 --> 00:01:46.450
machines. See you in the next one!
